3. **Predicting the Number of Smartphone Users in 2017 and 2019:**

   If you have past data on the number of smartphone users from 2016-2020, you can use the same linear regression method to predict the number of users in any given year.

   ```csharp
   // Example past data, replace with actual data if available
   Dictionary<int, double> smartphoneUsers = new Dictionary<int, double>
   {
       { 2016, 200.0 },
       { 2018, 220.0 },
       { 2020, 240.0 }
   };

   double predicted2017 = PredictSpecificYearValue(smartphoneUsers, 2017);
   double predicted2019 = PredictSpecificYearValue(smartphoneUsers, 2019);

   Console.WriteLine($"Predicted smartphone users in 2017: {predicted2017}");
   Console.WriteLine($"Predicted smartphone users in 2019: {predicted2019}");

   static double PredictSpecificYearValue(Dictionary<int, double> data, int year)
   {
       return PredictNextValue(data, year);
   }
   ```

This guide provides a basic framework. In a real-world scenario, you would use more sophisticated statistical methods and real data. For more accurate predictions, consider using libraries like ML.NET for machine learning models.
